# week2_project — Cursor rules (HCDE 530)

## Directory structure

<!-- Regenerate this block when files are added, removed, or renamed (see “Maintenance” below). -->

```
week2_project/
├── .cursorrules      # AI / editor rules for this folder
├── .gitignore
├── week2.md          # Competency claim (course reflection)
├── word_count.py     # CSV load, word counts, summary output
└── responses.csv     # Survey responses (participant_id, role, response)
```

## Maintenance (directory tree)

- **Humans & AI:** Whenever the project layout changes in a meaningful way, **update the tree above in the same change** so it stays accurate.
- Cursor does **not** auto-update this file; treating the tree as part of the “contract” avoids drift.

## Stack
- Python 3. Prefer the standard library (`csv`, `pathlib`, etc.) unless the assignment requires otherwise.
- Data lives next to scripts (e.g. `responses.csv`); use paths that work when run from the project folder.

## CSV
- Open with `encoding="utf-8"` and `newline=""` when using `csv.reader` / `csv.DictReader`.
- `DictReader` row keys **must match** the CSV header row exactly (`participant_id`, `role`, `response`, etc.). If headers change, update the keys in code.

## Style
- Keep comments **short and precise**; explain *why* or non-obvious behavior, not every line.
- Prefer small, clear functions (e.g. word counting separate from I/O) with accurate docstrings.
- Avoid drive-by refactors and unrelated files in a single change.

## Edits
- Match existing naming and structure in `word_count.py` and siblings.
- Do not add large dependencies, boilerplate, or course README files unless asked.

## Git
- This folder is its own repo; commit messages should describe the actual change in plain language.
